.Together the studies raise two important questions. Are we now relying too heavily on criminal prosecution in many areas? And would society’s objectives be better served through less punitive means? Alternatives include the use of rewards and administrative penalties, control by licensing and limiting exposure to and controlling opportunities for wrongdoing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLaw enforcementvCase studies. 0aReward (Law)vCase studies. 0aSanctions (Law)vCase studies. 0aSociological jurisprudencevCase studies. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aAddario, Susan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCondon, Mary G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewees, Donald N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoob, Anthony N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedland, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedland, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHagan, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMc Carthy, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLaren, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRankin, Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoach, Kent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRogerson, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShearing, Clifford D.